<p>Our neural pathways are not set up to remember lots of asinine details that are all disjointed from each other.Â  Instead, weâ€™re optimized to remember lots of little things that are somehow easily relatable to the bigger things that are somehow relevant to those original little(er) things in a way that makes us not forget them.Â   When the little things get too numerous to count, and when theyâ€™re not essential to even understanding how the bigger things work anymore, we need some help.Â   This is why pilots have checklists and drivers use maps; we need something visual.</p>

<p>What is the point of me (or you) studying some new programming language or framework unless weâ€™re going to start using it regularly?Â   You know youâ€™re just going to forget stuff so why bother at allâ€¦right?Â   The answer Iâ€™ve found to be true is this: There are two objectives to learning a new technology of any kind and they are:</p>

